        "title": "Summary — priority order",
        "content": "| Priority | Module | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `store.py` | Dedup correctness + the `next_seq` concurrency claim are load-bearing and totally unverified; memory flags this area as previously fragile ([[jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions]]). |\n| 2 | `models.py` / `filters.py` | Pure, cheap to test, and the forgiving-cutoff/date-parsing edge cases are exactly where silent regressions hide. |\n| 3 | `notify.py` | `dispatch()`'s entire purpose (error isolation) is unverified; a broken notifier could currently take down the whole run. |\n| 4 | `fetchers.py` retry/pagination | Shared `_request` backoff + per-ATS pagination stop-conditions are duplicated ~12 times with zero coverage — one bug here silently degrades every integration. |\n| 5 | `fetchers.py` parsers | High edge-case density (documented in comments) but easy/cheap to test since they're pure functions. |\n| 6 | `pipeline.py` | Small surface, but the dry-run/persist branch split is the one thing that must never regress (accidentally persisting during `--dry-run`). |\n| 7 | `agent.py` | CLI helpers wrapping `Store`; `_chrome_bin`/`cmd_pdf_render` need subprocess mocking or a CI-gated real-Chrome smoke test. |\n| 8 | `cli.py` | Trivial, do last. |\n\n**Structural note**: none of this can run without `pytest`, `pytest-asyncio`, and `respx` added to a new `requirements-dev.txt` (drafted above) — I couldn't verify these tests actually pass since shell/file-write access was denied in this session. Recommend running `pytest` locally after adding the files before trusting the skeletons marked `# TODO` are fully correct — a few (e.g. `test_workday_stops_when_offset_reaches_total`, the `_simple()` fetcher signature question) depend on details I inferred from reading rather than executing.",
